"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451157","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-24","<p>Further details of the purpose and availability of the transitional funding facility will be available in due course.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","26270","2016-02-24T15:02:58.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451157/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451157/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 3 February 2016 to Question 24265, what criteria colleges and post-16 educational institutions will have to meet in order to access the transitional funding facility allocated by his Department.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","26264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451158","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-24","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-26/24265/" target="_blank">24265</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-24T15:26:23.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451158/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451158/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 3 February 2016 to Question 24265, when he plans to (a) assess how many further education institutions are likely to incur financial penalties as a result of triggering break clauses in loan agreements they hold with banks resulting from his Department's area reviews and (b) publish such data.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","26265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451159","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Flexible working is now a key aspect of today’s employment landscape with a growing number of employees taking advantage of flexible working – either through an informal arrangement with their employer or through the statutory Right to Request Flexible Working. This was extended to all employees with 26 weeks qualifying service in June 2014 and at the same time it was made easier for employers to consider requests for flexible working.</p><p> </p><p>At the time this change was introduced, employers were encouraged to use the strapline “Happy to Talk Flexible Working” when advertising jobs. The Right to Request was promoted in various ways, including a conference for employers which explained the benefits of flexible working and provided practical tips and as part of the GREAT campaign.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-08T14:52:05.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451159/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451159/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Recruitment: Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to encourage businesses to advertise flexible working arrangements by default in job advertisements.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","26304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451160","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-08","<p>We do not publish details of penalties in individual cases. The employers named in the February 5th round were issued with a combined total of over £629,000 in penalties. To date, 84 of the 92 employers have paid penalties. The remaining 8 are being pursued by HM Revenue and Customs compliance officers.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-08T14:54:28.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451160/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451160/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the amount of financial penalties was for non-compliance with national minimum wage (a) imposed on and (b) paid by each of the 92 employers who were named and shamed by his Department for such non-compliance on 5 February 2015.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","26318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451161","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p>This information is published by the Office for National Statistics for all departments on an annual basis. The latest publication date was 8 October 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Detailed breakdowns of mean and median salaries for both men and women (including within BIS) are contained in the Civil Service Statistics 2015 Statistical Bulletin Tables (tables 24 to 35), available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-414427" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-414427</a></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-11T15:29:11.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451161/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451161/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the average pay is of (a) men and (b) women working in his Department.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","26333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451162","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p>The European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) and European Social Fund (ESF) are administered in London by the Greater London Authority. Annual allocations are set out in the London ERDF Operational Programme 2007-2013 and London ESF Regional Framework 2011-2013 which can be found on the Greater London Authority’s website. The allocations could be spent up to the end of 2015. Allocations were not broken down for each London borough but a full list of projects funded by ERDF can be found also on the Greater London Authority’s website. A list of projects funded by ESF can be found under ESF funding for London on the Department for Work and Pensions website on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-11T15:36:00.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451162/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451162/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","EU Grants and Loans: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much funding from the (a) European Regional Development Fund and (b) European Social Fund was spent in (i) London and (ii) each London borough in each year from 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","26175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451163","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p>The European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) and European Social Fund (ESF) are administered in London by the Greater London Authority and will respond to priorities set out in the European Structural and Investment Strategy prepared by the London Enterprise Panel and other local partners. The Strategy updated in February 2016 sets out the amounts to be spent in London from ERDF and ESF and can be found on the London Enterprise Panel website.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-11T15:34:00.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451163/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451163/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","EU Grants and Loans: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much funding from the (a) European Regional Development Fund and (b) European Social Fund he forecasts will be spent in (i) London and (ii) each London borough in each year from 2016 and 2020.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","26176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451164","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of jobs that will be created from the European Structural and Investment (ESI) Funds spent in London in the 2014-2020 programming period is set out in the ESI Funds strategy prepared by the London Enterprise Panel and other local partners which can be found on the London Enterprise Panel website.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-11T15:31:52.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451164/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451164/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","EU Grants and Loans: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the number of jobs that will be created as a result of funding from the European Structural and Investment Funds spent in London between 2016 and 2020.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","26177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451165","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has introduced measures to help businesses with the transition to the new National Living Wage. The Government is reducing corporation tax to 18% by 2020, setting the Annual Investment Allowance at a new permanent level of £200,000, and increasing the Employment Allowance from £2,000 to £3,000. The increase in the Employment Allowance means a business could employ four people on the National Living Wage and pay no National Insurance Contributions. It will benefit up to 590,000 employers and take up to 90,000 firms out of National Insurance Contributions altogether. These measures will help small businesses across the country.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-11T15:27:25.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451165/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451165/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Small Businesses: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what support his Department plans to make available to small companies operating in deprived areas to help meet the costs of the introduction of the living wage; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","26180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451166","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Government is committed to cutting £10bn worth of red tape, as set out in the 2015 Conservative Manifesto, and will report on progress by June this year. We are putting forward proposals in the Enterprise Bill to systematically track for the first time the impact of regulators’ actions. This will drive savings through, for instance, simpler guidance, less paperwork and coordinated inspections. Through my department’s Cutting Red Tape programme, businesses are encouraged to report burdens and recommend sectors that Government may wish to review. There are currently seven reviews in progress: Energy; Care; Agriculture; Mineral Extraction; Waste; Anti-Money Laundering; and House Building.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T17:33:01.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451166/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451166/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Business: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to reduce the burden of regulation on businesses.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","26212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451167","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p>Increasing exports, to all overseas markets, is a key factor in the Government’s long-term economic plan. Government departments are working together to support UK businesses looking to take advantage of overseas opportunities and to create a strong business environment that allows them to flourish both at home and overseas. A key part of this work is to identify export opportunities, many of which are based around the needs of high-growth and emerging markets.</p><p>This effort to drive economic growth is supported in part by the Prime Minister’s <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/trade-envoys" target="_blank">Trade Envoy Programme</a>, a group of appointed parliamentarians drawn from across the political spectrum. Envoys are carefully selected for their experience, skills and knowledge of particular sectors or markets, or their knowledge of business in an effort to identify substantial trade and investment opportunities. There are now 24 Trade Envoys covering 50 high-growth and emerging markets.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T17:31:16.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451167/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451167/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Trade Promotion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to promote trade opportunities for UK businesses in high-growth markets.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","26214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451168","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p>I have made it clear to local councils and Local Enterprise Partnerships who are administering the Business Recovery Grant that they should look to provide funding to un-insured businesses so long as it is clear that this is not rewarding deliberate bad business practice. So where a flooded business has made a reasonable effort to secure insurance and not been successful they can be funded. We have provided £11m in total to provide support to businesses, allocated to local areas based on the number of flooded businesses.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T17:32:26.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451168/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451168/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Business: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what funds the Government is providing for businesses affected by flooding which did not have insurance.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","26199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451169","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-24","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-26/24367/" target="_blank">24367</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-24T14:49:28.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451169/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451169/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-08","Further Education: Mergers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24499, what discussions his Department plans to have with banks on minimising the cost of loan and other penalties incurred by colleges which merge as part of area reviews.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","26224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451170","Department for Education","false","2016-02-11","<p>There is a duty on local authorities to judge what provision is appropriate to meet local needs in their areas. An overarching statutory framework places a legal duty on local authorities to have arrangements in place to secure sufficient children’s centres to meet local need and to consult where changes are planned to local children’s centre provision.</p><p>In deciding what arrangements to make, local authorities must have particular regard to the quality and quantity of early childhood services in the area. Local authorities are best placed to understand local needs and the different ways children and families can be supported locally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-02-11T10:10:21.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451170/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451170/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-08","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of super centres on smaller, privately-funded child care businesses located close to them.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","26253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451171","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-15","<p>The Civil Service requires a variety of skills and professions within its workforce and many senior civil servants, by nature of their remit, work closely with Ministers, which is why the majority of these positions are based in London.</p><p>The proportion of SCS based in London has remained relatively stable from 2010 to 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>1<sup>st</sup> April 2010</p></td><td><p>65.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1<sup>st</sup> April 2011</p></td><td><p>65.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1<sup>st</sup> April 2012</p></td><td><p>65.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1<sup>st</sup> April 2013</p></td><td><p>63.9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1<sup>st</sup> April 2014</p></td><td><p>65.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1<sup>st</sup> April 2015</p></td><td><p>67.0%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Although the proportion has increased, this represents an overall decrease in headcount, from 2,840 at 1<sup>st</sup> April 2010 to 2,660 at 1<sup>st</sup> April 2015.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-15T13:29:21.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451171/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451171/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-08","Senior Civil Servants: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 25009, what proportion of people in the Senior Civil Service were based in London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","26217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451172","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-16","<p>All contractors and suppliers are required to confirm that they are compliant with UK tax obligations in order to compete for contracts with the Cabinet Office<strong>. </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-16T15:26:14.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451172/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451172/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-08","Government Digital Service: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assurances the Government Digital Service seeks from its contractors and suppliers that they are fully compliant with their UK tax obligations.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","26226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451173","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>The National Citizen Service Trust works with the Cabinet Office to deliver (NCS) in England. There have been no accidents that the NCS Trust is aware of where insurance claims have been lodged.</p><p>The NCS delivery partner within Northern Ireland, Co-operation Ireland, has also confirmed that it has not received any correspondence from insurance companies in regards to claims relating to NCS accidents.</p><p>The Cabinet Office coordinated a pilot programme in Wales in 2014 and is not aware of any resulting insurance claims by participants.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-11T11:57:57.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451173/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451173/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-08","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many insurance claims have been lodged as a result of accidents occurring during participation in the National Citizen Service since the establishment of that scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","26228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451174","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-15","<p>The UK Government hosted the most recent British-Irish Council (BIC) Summit, in London, on 27 November 2015. At the Summit, the Council agreed a set of principles to make sure the BIC work sectors continue to deliver value for all Member Administrations. The UK Government is working with the other BIC Member Administrations to implement this work and will report back at future Summits. Further information can be found in the summit communique:</p><p><a href="http://www.britishirishcouncil.org/sites/default/files/communiqu%C3%A9s/London%20271115%20Communique.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.britishirishcouncil.org/sites/default/files/communiqu%C3%A9s/London%20271115%20Communique.pdf</a></p><p>The Government continues to operate the structures of the British-Irish Intergovernmental Conference in line with international agreements. There are no plans to develop its use. The UK enjoys a strong relationship with the Republic of Ireland.</p><p>To ensure that we continue to build on this strong foundation, the Prime Minister holds an annual summit with the Taoiseach at which they discuss mutual challenges and opportunities to work on issues of common interest. This is supported by an annual summit in the autumn between the Permanent Secretaries of the UK Government and Irish Government, which oversees and takes forward a joint work programme between the UK and Ireland governments.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-02-15T16:39:25.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451174/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451174/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-08","Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to develop (a) the British-Irish Council, (b) the British-Irish Intergovernmental Conference and (c) other such east-west structures.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","26301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451175","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>There is a long established secretariat in the Cabinet Office that deals with all European matters, including the renegotiation. This has been expanded in recent weeks to reflect the increased workload resulting from the renegotiation.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-02-11T16:59:21.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451175/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451175/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-08","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department has established a group or unit to deal with the Government approach to the forthcoming EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","26361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451176","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>We live in an unpredictable world and if a threat to the UK were to arise from a nuclear-armed adversary, we would seek to ensure that they were deterred from using nuclear weapons by convincing them that the costs to them of doing so greatly outweighed any gains they could hope to make.</p><p>Other chemical, biological, radiological and nuclear threats are considered as part of the National Security Risk Assessment and this is reflected in the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015. The Government’s approach to preparing for emergencies is to prepare for the common consequences of a range of civil emergencies. This is supplemented with proportionate planning and capability building for the highest impact and most concerning risks, of which a nuclear terrorist attack in the UK is one.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-02-11T11:58:51.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451176/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451176/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-08","Nuclear Weapons: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the emergency response plans are in the event of Russia firing a nuclear bomb.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","26344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451177","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have discussions with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available on Gov.uk.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:41:08.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451177/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451177/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Dividend Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with small and medium-sized enterprises on the proposed change to the dividend tax.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","26371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451178","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","I refer the honourable Member to my response of 16 June 2015 (UIN 2064)<p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-10/2064/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-10/2064/</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-11T17:28:16.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451178/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451178/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Child Benefit: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people receiving child benefit on behalf of children living outside of the UK.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","26359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451179","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-15","<p>The Government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage (NMW) receives it. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review all complaints that are referred to them.</p><p> </p><p>Full year figures for 2014/15 are provided in the ‘Final government evidence for the Low Pay Commission’s 2016 Report’, which is available to view at the following address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-minimum-wage-final-government-evidence-to-the-low-pay-commission-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-minimum-wage-final-government-evidence-to-the-low-pay-commission-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to cracking down on employers who break NMW law. Between April 2015 and November 2015, HMRC took action against over 500 businesses, identifying over £8 million for 46,000 workers. This is already the largest amount of arrears identified in any single year since the introduction of the NMW.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-15T12:54:28.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451179/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451179/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much was recovered by HM Revenue and Customs as arrears for non-compliance with the national minimum wage in each quarter since 1 April 2014; from how many employers that amount was recovered; and for how many workers that amount was recovered.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","26319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451180","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>The Successor delivery organisation that was announced in the Strategic Defence and Security Review will be overseen by the Ministry of Defence. As with any major programme of this scale an appropriate scrutiny process is in place.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-12T14:37:59.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451180/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451180/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the oral contribution of the Minister for Defence Procurement on 24 November 2015, Official Report, column 1254, in what ways his Department plans to exercise oversight of the Successor submarine programme.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451181","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs currently has no plans to issue compulsory redundancy notices to staff based at its Cumbernauld office within the next 12 months.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T13:44:56.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451181/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451181/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether there will be compulsory redundancy notices issued to staff based at HM Revenue and Customs Cumbernauld office in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","26274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451182","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-15","Details of the proposals for restricting in-work benefits for EU nationals will be subject to further negotiation and we cannot speculate on these.","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-15T10:07:00.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451182/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451182/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Social Security Benefits: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the savings to the public purse of the proposed emergency brake on in-work benefits for EU citizens in employment in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","26266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451183","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-16","Prior to engagement, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) require a new contractor or supplier to provide their tax details, and to agree to HMRC performing revenue compliance checks throughout the procurement process, using information from its own records and taking appropriate action where required in line with the Public Contracts Regulations 2015.<p><em> </em></p>Contracts for such engagements include clauses requiring that at all times the contractor or supplier shall comply with all statutes and regulations relating to direct or indirect taxes, and that failure to comply may constitute a material breach of the contract.<p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-16T16:02:55.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451183/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451183/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Revenue and Customs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assurances HM Revenue and Customs seeks from its contractors and suppliers that they are fully compliant with their UK tax obligations.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","26225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451184","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer keeps all taxes under review.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T13:51:49.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451184/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451184/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Personal Savings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of combining the ISA and personal pension systems.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","26230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451185","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>The UK has been at the forefront of international efforts to tackle corporate tax avoidance through the OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS) project, which was completed in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has committed to introducing country-by-country reporting from 1 January 2016 and rules to deal with hybrid mismatch arrangements from 1 January 2017. As set out in Autumn Statement 2014, these measures are estimated to yield around £45 million and £260 million respectively over the next five years. The policy costings were certified by the independent Office for Budget Responsibility.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also consulted on the OECD recommendations on the design of rules to prevent groups from gaining excessive tax deductions for interest expense, and how the OECD report on the definition of substantial activities in the context of preferential intellectual property regimes impacts the UK Patent Box.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:39:48.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451185/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451185/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Multinational Companies: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress the Government has made on the implementation of the OECD's Base Erosion and Profit Shifting programme; and what assessment he has made of the effect of that programme on the collection of corporation tax in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","26164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451186","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>As of 31 March 2010, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) employed 1500 full-time and 640 part-time staff in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>As of 31 March 2015, there were 1,050 full-time and 620 part-time staff.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T13:18:25.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451186/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451186/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Revenue and Customs: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what change there was in the number of (a) full-time and (b) part-time employees of HM Revenue and Customs in Northern Ireland between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","26227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451187","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>The Northern Powerhouse is the government’s plan to boost the economy across the North of England. This will help businesses grow and increase private sector job creation. Unlike previous failed attempts to improve the economic performance of the North, it is not about just creating publicly-funded jobs.</p><p> </p><p>There is already evidence that the Northern Powerhouse is working: according to the latest data, private sector employment outside of London and the South East increased by 1.5m between Q3 2010 and Q3 2015, and in the North alone there are almost 412,000 more people in work than in April 2010. Over the last year the number of people in employment in the North has grown faster than in the South. Employment in Cumbria has also grown by 6,700 (3%) since 2010 and 10,900 (4.7%) over the last year.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-12T14:38:51.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451187/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451187/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many publicly-funded jobs related directly to the Northern Powerhouse are located in (a) Cumbria, (b) Northern England, (c) London and (d) other parts of England.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","26203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451188","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Office of Tax Simplification (OTS) is already considering a wide range of issues relating to the taxation of contractors as part of its small companies review. It will report on its findings ahead of Budget.</p><p> </p><p>The topics of future OTS reviews will be announced in due course.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T13:56:21.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451188/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451188/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Self-employed: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will have discussions with the Office of Tax Simplification on reviewing and simplifying the tax regime for contractors.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","26247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451189","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>The first 12 months of local authorities’ resettlement costs are centrally funded using the overseas aid budget. In years 2-5, local authorities receive a per person tariff tapering from £5,000 to £1,000 over the four years. This is unringfenced funding and it is for local authorities to decide how best to use it to support refugees.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-02-16T13:00:23.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451189/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451189/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding the Government is providing to local authorities for each refugee for housing under the Syrian resettlement scheme (a) in London and (b) outside London.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","26220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451190","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>We are satisfied that the Scheme is consistent with the way in which Directive 41/2003 on the Institutions for Occupational Retirement Provision Directive was transposed into national law. It is not therefore necessary to take any further legislative steps to ensure compliance.</p><p>In March 2014 the European Commission published proposals for new Institutions for Occupational Retirement Provisions Directive. The implications for the scheme will be fully considered if these proposals are taken forward.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-16T13:04:20.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451190/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451190/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Local Government: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will apply EU Directive 41/2003 on Institutions for Occupational Retirement Provision to the Local Government Pension Scheme; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","26222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451191","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>Building Regulations require that building work is carried out with adequate and proper materials which are appropriate for the circumstances in which they are used. Building control bodies are responsible for checking compliance as with any other Building Regulations’ requirements. In addition, if a building material is covered by a harmonised European standard, the requirements of the European Construction Products Regulation will apply. This Regulation is enforced by local authorities (trading standards in England, Scotland and Wales and District Councils in Northern Ireland).</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-16T12:58:24.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451191/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451191/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to prevent the use of fraudulent roofing materials in the building of new houses.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","26223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451192","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-23","<p>Local authorities have a statutory duty to provide a comprehensive and efficient library service that takes account of local needs within available resources. Government has the power to ensure public libraries comply with the law, and where individual authorities have failed to meet this duty we will - and have - intervened. While the Department for Culture, Media and Sport does not commission specific information relating to the closure of public libraries, the Department monitors closely proposed changes to library service provision throughout England. Desk research undertaken by the Department indicates that no local static libraries closed in the Lancashire Library Authority in 2012 - 2015.</p><p> </p><p>This Government is helping libraries innovate, to ensure they serve the needs of local communities - particularly through the expansion of their digital offer. In the latest spending round we secured extra funding for our Libraries Task Force, set up in 2015, to promote the role of digital and share best practice between councils, and we have funded the rollout of free Wi-Fi so that it will be available in 99% of public libraries in England. E-book loans have rocketed more than four-fold from nearly 445,000 in 2011/12 to over 2.3 million in 2014/15.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-23T10:02:01.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451192/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451192/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","Public Libraries: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many local libraries closed in Lancashire in (a) 2012, (b) 2013, (c) 2014 and (d) 2015.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","26198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451193","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Department is unable to predict how many projects in West Cumbria will come forward for funding from the EU.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-11T15:47:34.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451193/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451193/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Regional Planning and Development: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many projects planned for West Cumbria will be (a) part-funded and (b) wholly-funded by the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","26153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451194","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Department is unable to confirm how many projects in West Cumbria have been part-funded by the EU in the last ten years. DCLG is able to confirm that during the 2007-13 European Regional Development Fund programme 11 projects were funded in Cumbria. The regulatory requirement is for applicants to provide 50% of match-funding to support investment. No European Regional Development Fund projects were wholly-funded by the EU in the last 10 years.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-11T15:28:37.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451194/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451194/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Regional Planning and Development: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many projects in West Cumbria have been (a) part-funded and (b) wholly-funded by the EU in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","26154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451195","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-12","<p>Fixed term tenancies will enable local councils to review on-going need for a tenancy and, if this is still the case, to issue a new tenancy for the same or a more suitable home.</p><p>Where existing lifetime tenants transfer, the provisions in the Bill ensure that local authorities retain a discretion to offer the tenant a further lifetime tenancy in their new home.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-12T12:52:32.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451195/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451195/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Tenancy Agreements: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to exempt victims of domestic abuse who move home to escape violence from the provisions on fixed term tenancies of the Housing and Planning Bill.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","26149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451196","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>The Department considers the definition of a house in multiple occupation, as set out in the Housing Act 2004, is appropriate and has no plans to change it. We have recently issued a technical discussion paper on whether to extend mandatory licensing to those houses in multiple occupation with fewer than three storeys and plan to publish our response and proposed next steps in the coming months.</p><p />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-16T12:51:39.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451196/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451196/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Multiple Occupation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if his Department will conduct an assessment of the appropriateness of the definition of houses in multiple occupation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","26307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451197","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>The Department published a technical discussion paper on licensing of houses in multiple occupation on 6 November 2015. We received representations from 170 local authorities which we are currently analysing. We plan to publish our response in the coming months.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-16T12:54:39.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451197/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451197/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Multiple Occupation: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations he has received from local councils on the application of (a) mandatory and (b) additional licensing for houses in multiple occupation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","26306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451198","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The numbers of licences issued for houses in multiple occupation during the relevant period were:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Coventry</p></td><td><p>233</p></td><td><p>216</p></td><td><p>282</p></td><td><p>357</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>1,426</p></td><td><p>2,997</p></td><td><p>3,284</p></td><td><p>3,562</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>34,464</p></td><td><p>36,256</p></td><td><p>27,182</p></td><td><p>38,530</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department only began collecting this data in 2011 and collects data in respect of England.</p><p>Source: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-housing-data</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T16:34:31.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451198/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451198/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Multiple Occupation: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the number of licences issued for houses of multiple occupation in (a) Coventry, (b) the West Midlands and (c) the UK in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","26305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451199","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>Administering authorities in the local government pension scheme in England and Wales have been asked to explain the proportion of their funds currently allocated to infrastructure projects and what proportion they intend to invest in infrastructure in the future. The benefits of scale achieved under the new pooling arrangements will enable authorities to be more ambitious and invest in infrastructure in a way that will help drive local growth.</p><p>Administering authorities have also been asked to submit their detailed proposals for pooling their assets, including their plans to invest in infrastructure, by 19 July. The proposals will then be assessed to establish whether they comply with the Department’s criteria for the pooling of scheme assets, including infrastructure.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-16T15:17:26.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451199/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451199/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Local Government: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if his Department will introduce a requirement that Local Government Pension Scheme funds be invested in infrastructure projects.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","26328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451200","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Department does not collect or hold information about the number of rent repayment orders issued in respect of unlicensed houses in multiple occupation.</p><p>A local authority may apply to the First Tier Tribunal (Property Chamber) for such an order if Housing Benefit was paid to cover or assist with rent payments during the period a house in multiple occupation was required to be licensed, but was not. Information about the number of rent repayment orders issued to local authorities will be held by the authorities themselves.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T16:36:06.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451200/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451200/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Multiple Occupation: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the number of rent repayment orders issued to houses in multiple occupation which were not adequately licensed in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","26334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451201","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Department has recently consulted on options for extending the scope of mandatory licensing to include those Houses in Multiple Occcupation in England with fewer than three storeys. We plan to announce our proposals and next steps in the spring.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T16:35:08.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451201/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451201/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Multiple Occupation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to categorise houses which are overcrowded and have fewer than three storeys as houses in multiple occupation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","26335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451202","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>Armed forces veterans injured in service receive payments through the War Disablement Pension or the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme. The latter applies to veterans injured from 6 April 2005. These payments are divided into a personal injury compensation element and other payments. Traditionally, only the personal injury compensation payment has been fully disregarded.</p><p>Since October 2012, Guaranteed Income Payments made to veterans under the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme have been disregarded. The Department of Health has been in discussion with the Royal British Legion about how War Disablement Pension payments are treated. Currently, the first £10 per week of these payments is disregarded. The Government is considering how these payments to veterans should be treated in the financial assessment for social care charging in future.</p><p>It is not the policy of this Government to ring-fence funding for particular purposes. This is to allow local authorities the flexibility to manage their own resources in the most efficient manner.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-16T13:02:27.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451202/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451202/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-08","Social Services: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if officials in his Department will have discussions with officials in the Department of Health on the establishment of a ring-fenced fund for local authorities to be able to disregard military compensation payments in financial assessments for social care.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","26311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451203","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Barnett Formula will be applied in the usual way to any additional funding from the Exchequer arising from the final local government finance settlement for 2016-17.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-11T14:00:06.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451203/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451203/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-08","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether any Barnett consequentials arise from the Local Government Finance Report (England) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","26364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451204","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>Our Satellite Broadband Scheme offers homes and businesses in some of the most remote areas of the UK a subsidised satellite broadband connection if they are currently unable to obtain an affordable broadband service of at least 2 Mbps.</p><p>The benefits of broadband are clear - and that is why we have introduced this subsidised offer to meet the Universal Service Commitment - which gives a first year only subsidy for a basic package capped at £400.</p><p>The total number of premises eligible for the universal service commitment subsidy had been substantially reduced, from around 11% in 2010 to around 1% by the end of 2015, as a result of roll-out superfast broadband by the commercial sector and through publicly-funded programmes.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-24T14:19:34.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451204/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451204/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the additional cost to rural broadband subscribers of paying separately for satellite broadband and telephony; and what the impact of such costs is on the rural economy.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","26363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451205","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-11","<p>I refer the honourable member to my response to PQ 22672, submitted to Parliament on 19 January.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-11T11:00:29.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451205/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451205/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to publish the outcome of the consultation on the BBC Charter Renewal process.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","26353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451206","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Government is working with commercial broadband providers to encourage them to fill the remaining gaps in superfast broadband coverage in London. BT has announced £50 million of investment in new commercial coverage, much of which will be aimed at London, and Virgin Media has announced a demand led investment programme of £3 billion over the next few years. Other suppliers are also active in London.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of commercially-led delivery and public funding in areas which are not commercially viable, superfast broadband coverage across the UK now reaches almost 90% of premises, providing access to speeds of more than 24Mbps. Coverage is on track to increase to 95% of premises by December 2017. The Government has also announced proposals for a Universal Service Obligation to enable all premises to request a broadband speed of at least 10Mbps, with the aim of implementing it in this Parliament. A basic broadband scheme has also been introduced across the UK allowing all premises with speeds below 2Mbps to gain access to speeds above this level through a subsidised satellite broadband connection.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-11T11:02:02.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451206/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451206/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent steps his Department has taken to tackle disparities in broadband coverage in (a) London and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","26315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451207","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-11","<p>It is a matter for Ofcom to monitor and regulate competition in electronic communications markets and last year it launched a Strategic Review of Digital Communications. Maintaining and promoting competition and innovation in the electronic communications markets are key areas that Ofcom is considering.</p><p> </p><p>The promotion of competition and innovation in the telecommunications sector is high on the Government’s list of objectives for the European Commission’s review of the Electronic Communications regulatory Framework, as was reflected in our response to its consultation. Proposals from the Commission are expected later this year.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-11T10:59:29.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451207/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451207/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to (a) encourage innovation and competition amongst broadband network providers and (b) reduce monopoly control over broadband infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","26268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451208","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>DCMS museums operate at arm’s length from government and the transfer of objects between national museums is a matter for the boards of the museums. The Trustees of the Science Museum approved the transfer of the Royal Photographic Society’s collection to the V&amp;A, and the Royal Photographic Society also approve of the transfer. The Department was informed in December 2015.</p><p>The V&amp;A intend to store, digitise and make the photographic collection available as part of its planned International Photography Resource Centre, which will provide the public with a world-class facility to access the consolidated collection.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-24T13:54:59.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451208/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451208/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","Royal Photographic Society","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department has been consulted on the transfer of the Royal Photographic Society's collection from the National Media Museum to the Victoria and Albert Museum.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","26166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451209","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>The National Media Museum in Bradford holds the National Photographic Collection, which has over 3 million photographic objects. DCMS museums operate at arm’s length from government and the transfer of objects between national museums is a matter for the boards of the museums.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-24T13:53:55.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451209/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451209/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","National Photography Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his policy is on a National Photography Museum.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","26167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451210","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Government continues to support the fantastic range of arts in the culture in Yorkshire and the Humber through its public investment in the arts, distributed by Arts Council England, as well as investment in cultural projects and programmes including £1.5 million for the Ferens Art Gallery in Hull to support its redevelopment and £1 million to support the Yorkshire Festival which will celebrate the region’s culture this summer.</p><p> </p><p>The Arts Council has provided the following funding to Yorkshire during the dates specified:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Funding Year</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/2016: 1st April - 8 Feb 2016</p></td><td><p>£46,399,085</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p /><p /><p /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Funding Year</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/2011</p></td><td><p>£36,013,760</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/2012</p></td><td><p>£47,661,513</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/2013</p></td><td><p>£64,126,617</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>£46,717,549</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>£53,628,743</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-15T09:01:58.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451210/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451210/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-08","Arts: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department spent on access to the arts in Yorkshire and Humber region between (a) May 2015 and February 2016 and (b) May 2010 and April 2015.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","26168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451211","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The number of reconnaissance, combat and other missions between 1 February 2015 and 1 February 2016 are detailed in the table below. The majority of aircraft flying missions in Syrian airspace will have flown over Iraqi airspace as well. Reaper, Tornado and Typhoon are multi-role aircraft and as such can be deployed in both a combat mission and a reconnaissance mission. Other missions have been defined as those involved in the transportation of people or equipment.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Syria</p></td><td><p>Iraq</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Reconnaissance Missions</p></td><td><p>435</p></td><td><p>906</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Combat Missions</p></td><td><p>64</p></td><td><p>699</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>484*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*This figure does not include C17, which is estimated to have flown two missions a month in the period in question. The records for C17 are not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","26133","2016-02-11T16:22:38.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451211/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451211/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Iraq: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) reconnaissance, (b) combat and (c) other missions were flown by RAF aircraft over Iraq in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","26132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451212","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The number of reconnaissance, combat and other missions between 1 February 2015 and 1 February 2016 are detailed in the table below. The majority of aircraft flying missions in Syrian airspace will have flown over Iraqi airspace as well. Reaper, Tornado and Typhoon are multi-role aircraft and as such can be deployed in both a combat mission and a reconnaissance mission. Other missions have been defined as those involved in the transportation of people or equipment.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Syria</p></td><td><p>Iraq</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Reconnaissance Missions</p></td><td><p>435</p></td><td><p>906</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Combat Missions</p></td><td><p>64</p></td><td><p>699</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>484*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*This figure does not include C17, which is estimated to have flown two missions a month in the period in question. The records for C17 are not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","26132","2016-02-11T16:22:38.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451212/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451212/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) reconnaissance, (b) combat and (c) other missions were flown by RAF aircraft over Syria in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","26133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451213","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-16","<p>We expect to approve the next stage of the Successor submarine programme later in 2016.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-16T15:56:52.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451213/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451213/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he expects the (a) demonstration phase and (b) manufacture phase of the Successor submarine programme to begin.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451214","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-15","<p>Centrally held contingency funding for the Defence Equipment Plan (EP) was introduced for the first time in 2012, at which point it totalled £4.8 billion over the 10 year planning period. The level of contingency has remained broadly stable over the subseqent four years, as shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p>EP Contingency by Financial Year</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>10 Year Total</p></td><td><p>£4.8 billion</p></td><td><p>£4.7 billion</p></td><td><p>£4.6 billion</p></td><td><p>£4.3 billion</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-15T15:46:10.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451214/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451214/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Defence Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the amount set aside for contingency funding was within the overall equipment budget of his Department in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451215","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-15","<p>The Long Overhaul Period (Refuel) of HMS Vengeance between March 2012 and December 2015 was carried out under a contract worth just over £350 million.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-15T15:47:03.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451215/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451215/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","HMS Vengeance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost was of refitting and refuelling HMS Vengeance between March 2012 and December 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451216","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-15","<p>A total of 32 Sea King aircraft are planned to be taken out of service during 2016:</p><p>10 Mk3</p><p>2 Mk3a</p><p>9 Mk4</p><p>11 Mk5</p><p>The Search and Rescue role provided by these Sea King helicopters is to be delivered by contractor-provided services. Other roles delivered by these aircraft will transition to the Merlin fleet operated by the Royal Navy.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-15T15:55:47.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451216/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451216/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Sea King Helicopters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 3 February 2016 to Question 24277, how many Sea King (a) Mk3, (b) Mk3a, (c) Mk4 and (d) Mk5 aircraft are planned to be taken out of service in 2016; and what plans the Government has to replace those assets.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451217","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The table below shows the total number of maritime patrol aircraft (MPA), from the US, Canada, France and Germany, temporarily deployed to RAF Lossiemouth at some point during 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Country</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of aircraft</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>US</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Canada</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>France</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-11T16:21:35.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451217/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451217/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","RAF Lossiemouth: Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2016 to Question 24281, how many maritime patrol aircraft from (a) the US, (b) Canada, (c) France and (d) Germany were temporarily deployed to RAF Lossiemouth in 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451218","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The information requested is provided below. In answering this question, I have defined 'deployed on operations' as times away from UK waters for extended periods.</p><p>In 2011, the Type 42 Destroyers were deployed on operations. No Type 45 Destroyer was deployed away from the UK.</p><p> </p><p><strong>2012</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Ship</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Deployment</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Days</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DARING</p></td><td><p>Operation Kipion: Gulf Region</p></td><td><p>210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DAUNTLESS</p></td><td><p>Atlantic Patrol Tasking (South)</p></td><td><p>209</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DIAMOND</p></td><td><p>Operation Kipion: Gulf Region</p></td><td><p>191</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>2013</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Ship</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Deployment</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Days</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DRAGON</p></td><td><p>Operation Kipion: Gulf Region</p></td><td><p>254</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DARING</p></td><td><p>Global Deployment</p></td><td><p>277</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>2014</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Ship</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Deployment</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Days</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DIAMOND</p></td><td><p>Operation Recsyr: protecting and escorting ships transporting chemicals from Syria</p></td><td><p>163</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DEFENDER</p></td><td><p>Operation Kipion: Gulf Region</p></td><td><p>193</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS DRAGON</p></td><td><p>Atlantic Patrol Tasking (South)</p></td><td><p>198</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>When not deployed on operations, all Type 45 ships would have undertaken activities such as sea trials, training, engagement, provisioning or been in a maintenance period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-11T16:20:22.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451218/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451218/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Type 45 Destroyers: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 25004, (a) for how many days (a) HMS Daring, (b) HMS Dauntless, (c) HMS Diamond, (d) HMS Dragon, (e) HMS Defender and (f) HMS Duncan were deployed on operations and (b) in which theatre they were so deployed in (i) 2011, (ii) 2012, (iii) 2013 and (iv) 2014.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451219","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>For the Offshore Patrol Vessels (OPV) currently under construction around 4,000 tonnes of steel is needed in total for the three ships. Dent Steel Services (UK) was awarded the contract by BAE Systems to source and supply the steel required for the OPVs.</p><p> </p><p>Around 60 per cent of the total steel required for the OPVs consists of thin plate (between four and five millimeters ) which can be sourced only from steel mills capable of rolling the material to that thickness.</p><p> </p><p>UK steel suppliers were approached by Dent but none were able to meet the thickness specification. As a result this steel was sourced from overseas suppliers.</p><p> </p><p>Around 60 per cent of the overall requirement was sourced from Sweden; 20 per cent from UK steel mills; 10 per cent from Spain; and the remaining 10 per cent from Dent's existing stock, of unknown origin. The use of overseas suppliers was necessary to obtain the required specification of steel at a competitive price for delivery at the time required.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-11T16:29:29.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451219/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451219/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Warships: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 25075, from which countries steel was sourced for the manufacture of the offshore patrol vessels currently under construction; and what proportion of that steel was sourced from each such country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451220","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The primary cause of the greater repair and maintenance costs for HMS DIAMOND was a longer Docking Period than the other two routine docking cycles. HMS DARING and HMS DAUNTLESS are the only other Type 45 Destroyers to have completed a routine docking cycle. The additional length of the Docking Period was a reflection of the number of capability upgrades and modifications, fitted to HMS DIAMOND. This was entirely normal for a class of warship of this age and all future Docking Periods for the Class are now programmed for a similar duration.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-11T16:31:17.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451220/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451220/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","HMS Diamond","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 25006, for what reason the repair and maintenance costs of HMS Diamond were greater than those of the other Type 45 Destroyers.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","26252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451221","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Defence Cyber Operations Group was designed to deliver cyber capability and mainstream cyber security throughout Defence by establishing a federation of cyber units. As this work matured it resulted instead in the formation of the Joint Forces Cyber Group in May 2013.</p><p>The Joint Forces Cyber Group (JFCyG) plans and co-ordinates cyber operations, and develops new tactics, techniques and plans to deliver military capabilities to confront high-end threats. It comprises Joint Cyber Units at Cheltenham and Corsham, the Joint Cyber Unit (Reserve) and Information Assurance Units.</p><p>I am withholding details on the JFCyG as their disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","26325","2016-02-11T16:32:13.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451221/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451221/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Defence Cyber Operations Group: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the budget of the Defence Cyber Operations Group was in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","26326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451222","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>We are significantly growing the number of dedicated Cyber specialists in the Reserves. Recruiting is on track to meet our target by April 2017. As with other sensitive Defence capabilities, I am withholding the information requested as its disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-11T16:28:49.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451222/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451222/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Reserve Forces: Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many of the reserve forces are cyber specialists.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","26327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451223","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Defence Cyber Operations Group was designed to deliver cyber capability and mainstream cyber security throughout Defence by establishing a federation of cyber units. As this work matured it resulted instead in the formation of the Joint Forces Cyber Group in May 2013.</p><p>The Joint Forces Cyber Group (JFCyG) plans and co-ordinates cyber operations, and develops new tactics, techniques and plans to deliver military capabilities to confront high-end threats. It comprises Joint Cyber Units at Cheltenham and Corsham, the Joint Cyber Unit (Reserve) and Information Assurance Units.</p><p>I am withholding details on the JFCyG as their disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","26326","2016-02-11T16:32:13.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451223/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451223/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Defence Cyber Operations Group: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff make up the Defence Cyber Operations Group.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","26325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451224","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-16","<p>The Government has a long standing policy not to comment on intelligence matters.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-16T16:02:28.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451224/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451224/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-08","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether there are Reaper Ground Control Stations available for use by UK Reaper Squadrons 13 and 39 in North Africa.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","26356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451225","Department for Education","false","2016-02-16","<p>In key stage 1 (ages 5 to 7), pupils are taught about the main external body parts and teachers are able to teach pupils as is appropriate for their needs. At key stage 2 (ages seven to 11), pupils learn about changes to the human body as it grows from birth to old age. Puberty and body parts are important parts of this.</p><p> </p><p>All schools must have regard to the Department’s “Keeping Children Safe in Education” statutory guidance when carrying out their duties to safeguard and promote the welfare of children. This guidance requires governing bodies and proprietors to consider how children may be taught about safeguarding, including online, through teaching and learning opportunities, as part of a broad and balanced curriculum. This may include covering relevant issues through Personal, Social, Health and Economic (PSHE) education and through Sex and Relationships Education. The Department is in the process of consulting on changing the requirement from the need to “consider how children may be taught” to “ensure children are taught”.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-16T12:37:09.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451225/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451225/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-08","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to make it compulsory for primary schools to teach (a) the correct names for genitalia, (b) that genitals are private to the child and (c) where children should seek help if they are abused.","false","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","26352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451226","Department for Education","false","2016-02-16","<p>This Government believes that all children should have the opportunity to receive a high quality and appropriate sex and relationship education (SRE). SRE is compulsory in all maintained secondary schools and many primary schools also teach it in an age-appropriate way. The Government also expects academies and free schools to deliver SRE as part of their provision of a broad and balanced curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>Any state-funded school teaching SRE must have regard to the Secretary of State’s SRE guidance (2000). The Department does not collect data about the number of schools that follow the guidance. The Department has received requests about updating the existing SRE guidance which we will carefully consider.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted does not inspect individual curriculum subjects. However, aspects of Personal Social, Health and Economic (PSHE) education and SRE will inform its judgment on personal development, behaviour and welfare. Inspectors must also consider the spiritual, moral, social and cultural development of pupils. Schools have responsibility for acting upon the inspection reports they receive and any weaknesses will be considered when the school is next inspected.</p><p> </p><p>Initial Teacher Training is currently determined by the Teachers’ Standards, which all trainee teachers must be able to demonstrate by the end of their training. The Standards set out the key principles of good subject pedagogy and the importance of subject knowledge development across the curriculum. Schools and headteachers are best placed to determine which staff learning activities will be most beneficial for their schools and we expect them to lead the personal development of their teachers to improve the quality of all round teaching.</p><p> </p><p>The Department supports schools’ efforts to improve PSHE teaching, by drawing schools’ attention to a range of high quality PSHE education teaching resources, including quality resources, lesson plans, a programme of study, factsheets and case studies. These resources are kite-marked by the PSHE Association to ensure that schools can trust the materials they use and improve their teaching.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","26329 ; 26330 ; 26331","2016-02-16T12:47:50.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451226/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451226/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-08","Sex and Relationship Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to make sex and relationship training mandatory for all the teachers.","false","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","26332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451227","Department for Education","false","2016-02-11","<p>For the period December 2013 to July 2015 (2007-2013 European Social Fund programme extended to 2015), £71 million of ring fenced European Social Fund monies was available to provide support for young people aged 14-19 who were not in education, employment or training or, who were at risk of being so. The funding was administered by the Skills Funding Agency on behalf of the Education Funding Agency.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-02-11T10:03:30.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451227/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451227/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-08","Department for Education: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the amount of EU funding her Department received in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","26338"
