"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450975","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-15","<p><strong>Up to the end of January 2016, Concentrix have changed around 4800 out of around 419,000 decisions that they have taken since the start of the contract. These changed decisions are often as a result of new information provided by the claimant that had not been provided at the time of the original decision. The 4800 changed decisions includes some awards that were cancelled and others that were amended. </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-15T11:54:29.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450975/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450975/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many cancellations of tax credits by Concentrix have been reversed since that company's contract with his Department commenced.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","26041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450976","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-15","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) targets for responding to written correspondence received via post are to reply to 80% within 15 working days and 95% within 40 working days.</p><p> </p><p>The volume of written correspondence received by HMRC has decreased over the past three years, and is currently at around one million items per month. HMRC regularly publishes general performance reports on Gov.uk.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-15T11:10:16.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450976/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450976/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has target times for responding to written correspondence from members of the public; and what change there has been in the volume of written correspondence to HMRC from the public seeking information or assistance over the last three years.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","26021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450977","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>As an integral part of its overall debt policy, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses private sector debt collection agencies as additional resource capacity, to extend the reach of its debt recovery activities (currently around 3% of all collection activity), particularly in relation to high volume, low value, debts. This ensures that all debts are kept in active recovery, and releases HMRC staff to focus on higher value more complex cases.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:34:56.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450977/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450977/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Revenue and Customs: Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the policy of HM Revenue and Customs is on using debt collection agencies to retrieve outstanding tax payments from (a) individuals and (b) businesses.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","26027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450978","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold this data. However, they regularly publish general performance reports at Gov.uk.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:36:35.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450978/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450978/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many letters to HM Revenue and Customs from members of the public remained unanswered after (a) four, (b) eight and (c) 12 weeks in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","26018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450979","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs contracts the supplier BancTec to process cheques received from customers. Cheques are passed to BancTec on the day they are received, 99% of the cheques received are banked on the day of receipt. Over the last 12 months there was only one occasion when the cheques were not banked on the day of receipt. In one percent of cases further information is required, usually from the customer, to enable the cheque to be processed. Generally, all cases that require investigation are resolved within four working days.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:29:23.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450979/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450979/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Revenue and Customs: Cheques","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many cheques sent to HM Revenue and Customs from members of the public remained uncashed for (a) four, (b) eight and (c) 12 weeks in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","26016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450980","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold this data. However, they regularly publish general performance reports at Gov.uk.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:22:54.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450980/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450980/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the incidence of members of the public receiving multiple letters from HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) conveying conflicting information; and what steps HMRC is taking to reduce such occurrences.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","26019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450981","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-10","<p>All public servants, including special advisers, are subject to an overall 1% pay remit.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","25245","2016-02-10T13:47:59.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450981/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450981/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-05","Ministerial Policy Advisers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what criteria and pay grades his Department uses to decide on pay rises for political aides and special advisors.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","26025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450982","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has taken major steps to improve their customer service, including recruiting 3,000 new staff into customer service roles and undertaking their biggest-ever training programme to enable them to build customer support teams that can move across a wide range of work according to customer demand. HMRC have also introduced digital mail scanning to help manage the more than 1million items of post they receive every month.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:24:06.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450982/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450982/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has to improve HM Revenue and Customs' response times to written correspondence from members of the public.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","26020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450983","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>Such a review has not been carried out recently. However, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) regularly publish general performance reports at Gov.uk. HMRC targets for post are to reply to 80% within 15 working days, 95% within 40 working days, and 90% accuracy.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-12T14:25:03.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450983/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450983/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the efficiency of HM Revenue and Customs in handling written correspondence from members of the public.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","26015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450984","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>The UK’s starting point in negotiations of tax treaties is based closely on the OECD Model Double Taxation Convention, which is also the basis for most other countries’ tax treaties. Some developing countries prefer to follow the UN Model Convention, the provisions of which differ in some areas to the OECD Model and the UK has agreed to adopt some of the UN provisions in its treaties with those countries. The object of the negotiations is to produce a text acceptable to both countries, balancing their preferences and reflecting compromises.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-10T16:37:15.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450984/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450984/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Double Taxation: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what principles or framework HM Revenue and Customs uses to negotiate tax treaties with developing countries.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","26067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450985","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-10T16:42:59.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450985/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450985/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many and what proportion of tax credit claims reviewed by Concentrix have, following the review process, been paid in full; and for how long each such claim was suspended.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","26098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450986","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>Negotiating double taxation treaties involves a number of stages including the requirement for ministerial and parliamentary approval in both countries. Even once the substantive provisions have been agreed, finalising certain technical issues is an unpredictable process over which the United Kingdom is not fully in control. It is therefore not possible to say which treaties will be ready for signature in the next 12 months. However, HM Revenue and Customs does publish the programme of tax treaty negotiations and news of signed treaties at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/double-taxation-agreements-developments-and-planned-negotiations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/double-taxation-agreements-developments-and-planned-negotiations</a>.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-10T16:30:30.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450986/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450986/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-05","Double Taxation: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what double taxation treaties the Government expects to sign in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","26119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450987","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-10","<p>Council tax rates are completely up to local councils. All local authorities have the power to freeze council tax if they wish. Any council that wants to raise council tax above the referendum principle needs to go to their local area for consent.</p><p>Given the pressures councils face providing adult social care we are giving them the freedom to levy a 2 percent precept to help cover costs. Again, it is up to the responsible authority if they wish to exercise this.</p><p>Even if all authorities increase by the maximum under the referendum principles, council tax will still be lower in 2019-20 in real terms compared to 2010.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-10T16:49:23.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450987/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450987/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-05","Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 21 January 2016 to Question 23515, what estimate he has made of the total cost to people who pay council tax in (a) Stevenage, (b) Hertfordshire and (c) England of the potential increase in council tax; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","26101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450988","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The number of households accepted as being owed a main homelessness duty in each region of England in the last five financial years is shown in the atttached table.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-11T13:26:38.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450988/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450988/answer","PQ 26095.docx","PQ 26095.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450988/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-05","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people were recorded as homeless in each region in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","26095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450989","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>This Government recognises the importance of Digital Inclusion, and remains committed to seeing an improvement in the provision of digital information services for disabled people. Annual correspondence with the FTSE 100 companies has indicated that from 2013 to present there has been a steady increase in the number of companies that provide video relay. We welcome this positive progress, and public facing Government departments will continue to work with interested parties to ensure this continues.</p><p><br>We have also been monitoring progress of the provision of access services for Video on Demand (VoD) content since 2013 through engagement with the Authority for Television on Demand (ATVOD), platform operators content providers and broadcasters.</p><p><br>The Alliance for Digital Accessibility (formerly the Digital Accessibility Alliance), which has met twice since its formation, has created the environment for members to engage and discuss Accessibility issues.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","26054","2016-02-26T13:24:23.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450989/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450989/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-05","Digital Accessibility Alliance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what work the Digital Accessibility Alliance has completed or published since it was formed.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","26055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450990","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-16","<p>This information is set out in the Department's Annual Report and Accounts. The Queen Elizabeth II Conference Centre was valued during March 2010 and the total valuation was reported at £25,000,000. It was valued again during March 2015 and the total valuation was reported at £38,500,000. Dividend payments received by the Department from the Queen Elizabeth II Conference Centre trading fund for the five years are as set out below:-</p><p>2010-11 - £1,200,000</p><p>2011-12 - £1,200,000</p><p>2012-13 - £2,250,000 (exceptional dividend received due to Olympic event)</p><p>2013-14 - £1,500,000</p><p>2014-15 - £1,500,000.</p><p />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-16T12:44:18.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450990/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450990/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-05","Queen Elizabeth II Conference Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much has accrued to the public purse from the Queen Elizabeth II Conference Centre in each of the last five complete financial years.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","26030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450991","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-10","<p>Northstar Ventures manages five funds that have received funding from the European Regional Development Fund 2000-06 and 2007-13 Programme periods.</p><p>Three of these funds are closed to new investments and Northstar Ventures is exiting from remaining deals. This is likely to conclude by February 2017.</p><p>Two remaining funds - Proof of Concept and Accelerator Fund - will remain open to new investments until June 2016.</p><p>No changes to management arrangements are planned. Northstar Ventures will remain responsible for concluding the funds up to 2020. The Department of Communities and Local Government will remain responsible for directing the use of any legacy funding generated by the funds.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-10T16:46:54.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450991/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450991/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-05","Northstar Ventures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the remaining time period is of Northstar Ventures' funding through the European Regional Development Funds; and what changes are planned in the terms and control of that funding.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","26044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450992","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>This Government recognises the importance of Digital Inclusion, and remains committed to seeing an improvement in the provision of digital information services for disabled people. Annual correspondence with the FTSE 100 companies has indicated that from 2013 to present there has been a steady increase in the number of companies that provide video relay. We welcome this positive progress, and public facing Government departments will continue to work with interested parties to ensure this continues.</p><p><br>We have also been monitoring progress of the provision of access services for Video on Demand (VoD) content since 2013 through engagement with the Authority for Television on Demand (ATVOD), platform operators content providers and broadcasters.</p><p><br>The Alliance for Digital Accessibility (formerly the Digital Accessibility Alliance), which has met twice since its formation, has created the environment for members to engage and discuss Accessibility issues.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","26055","2016-02-26T13:24:23.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450992/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450992/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-05","Digital Accessibility Alliance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many times the Digital Accessibility Alliance has met in each quarter since it was formed.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","26054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450994","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Government is committed to implementing measures to address any barriers that prevent UK steel suppliers from competing effectively for public sector contracts. To that end, new guidelines for departments on sourcing and buying steel for major projects were published in October 2015. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) has written to its largest defence contractors to highlight these guidelines, which emphasise the importance of pre-market engagement, including through industry days and signalling future pipelines for steel.</p><p> </p><p>The MOD would not routinely meet with trades unions on this type of issue and has not received any representations. It has met with the UK steel industry through its membership of the Cabinet Office Steel Procurement Working Group. This group is looking to ensure that UK steel suppliers can compete on a level playing field with international suppliers on major projects.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-10T16:40:45.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450994/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450994/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-05","Defence Equipment: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department plans to take to engage with (a) industry bodies and (b) trades unions on the sourcing of steel for equipment procured by his Department from UK suppliers.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","26045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450995","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The amounts paid as a result of claims brought by internal and external claimants including claimants' legal costs from Financial Year (FY) 2010-11 to FY2013-14 are shown below. The costs for FY 2014-15 are being finalised and will be published shortly.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Internal Claimants</strong></p><p> </p><p>The amounts paid in compensation, including claimants' legal costs, for claims brought against the Ministry of Defence (MOD) by members and former members of HM Forces and civilian employees since 2010 are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Employers Liabilty Claims (including Service personnel and civilian staff)</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FY 2010-11</p></td><td><p>FY 2011-12</p></td><td><p>FY 2012-13</p></td><td><p>FY 2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£83.9 million</p></td><td><p>£62.0 million</p></td><td><p>£69.5 million</p></td><td><p>£58.5 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The vast majority of clinical negligence claims are brought by current or former members of HM Armed Forces but a small number will relate to their dependants treated in MOD medical facilities. The amounts paid in compensation, including claimants' legal costs, for these claims since 2010 are as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Clinical Negligence Claims</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FY 2010-11</p></td><td><p>FY 2011-12</p></td><td><p>FY 2012-13</p></td><td><p>FY 2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£17.0 million</p></td><td><p>£6.7 million</p></td><td><p>£7.1 million</p></td><td><p>£5.8 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>External Claimants</strong></p><p> </p><p>Public Liability Claims</p><p> </p><p>The amounts paid in compensation, including claimants' legal costs, for public liability claims brought against the MOD by third parties, including civilians both in the UK and overseas, relating to personal injury or property damage since 2010 are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FY 2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£5.4 million</p></td><td><p>£10.0 million</p></td><td><p>£25.0 million</p></td><td><p>£11.1 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Third Party Motor Claims in UK</p><p> </p><p>The amounts paid in compensation, including claimants' legal costs, for claims brought against the MOD by third parties involved in collisions with MOD-operated vehicles since 2010 are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FY 2010-11</p></td><td><p>FY 2011-12</p></td><td><p>FY 2012-13</p></td><td><p>FY 2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£5.6 million</p></td><td><p>£6.7 million</p></td><td><p>£4.8 million</p></td><td><p>£5.0 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Area Claims Offices</p><p> </p><p>The amounts paid in compensation, including claimants' legal costs, for claims brought against the MOD by third parties that are managed by the MODs regional Area Claims Offices since 2010 are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FY 2010-11</p></td><td><p>FY 2011-12</p></td><td><p>FY 2012-13</p></td><td><p>FY 2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£3.0 million</p></td><td><p>£1.8 million</p></td><td><p>£1.7 million</p></td><td><p>£1.5 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-02-11T16:34:15.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450995/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450995/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-05","Ministry of Defence: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has paid out in compensation to (a) internal and (b) external claimants in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","26087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450996","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-02-11T16:28:15.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450996/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450996/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-05","Military Bases: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of non-combatant deaths on military bases have been subject to an inquest by jury in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","26084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450997","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-15","<p>The finding not yet formally closed out in the Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator (DNSR) assessment of Exercise Senator 2011 called for a review of the hazard assessment for the transport operation. This is to ensure that protection measures remain proportionate to the risk and continue to be based on up-to-date scientific and regulatory advice. DNSR continues to have confidence in the adequacy of the arrangements currently in place, as has been demonstrated at emergency response exercises, but believes it is timely to conduct a review.</p><p>We currently expect the finding to be closed out within the next 12 months.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-15T15:45:20.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450997/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450997/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-05","Nuclear Weapons: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23641, which of the five findings contained in the Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator assessment of Exercise Senator 2011 has not been formally closed out.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","26093"
