"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451052","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Local Government Boundary Commission for England informs me that the procedure for electoral reviews is set out in the <em>Local Democracy, Economic Democracy and Construction Act 2009</em>. The Act requires the Commission to publish recommendations and consider representations made on them.</p><p>In drawing up new ward or electoral division boundaries, Section 58 of the Act requires the Commission to take into consideration any representations made to the Local Government Boundary Commission for England within its consultation periods.</p><p>In practice, the Commission always conducts at least two phases of public consultation for every electoral review. First, in advance of drawing up draft recommendations, the Commission will invite local proposals for new ward or electoral division boundaries.</p><p>Following the initial consultation, the Commission publishes draft recommendations and consults on them before finalising ward boundaries and the wider electoral arrangements for a local authority.</p><p>After each phase of consultation, the Commission will consider all local representations against the statutory criteria which are set out in Schedule 2 of the <em>Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Act 2009</em>. The criteria oblige the Commission to have regard to delivering electoral equality for voters, to build electoral arrangements that reflect community interests and identities as well as ensuring that wards or divisions promote effective and convenient local government.</p><p>The Commission analyses all local representations to assess the extent to which they meet the statutory criteria. If submissions present a fair reflection of the criteria and can be accommodated within an authority-wide scheme, it will usually adopt them. In the event that multiple (but conflicting) submissions meet the statutory criteria, the Commission will choose the option which it believes most strongly reflects them. If no local representations provide a satisfactory reflection of the statutory criteria, the Commission will substitute its judgement and draw up its own pattern of wards or divisions for the area in question.</p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2016-02-10T10:57:09.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451052/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451052/answer",,,,,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2016-02-05","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, whether the Local Government Boundary Commission is under an obligation to ensure that proposals for boundary changes reflect representations it has received from people in the areas affected.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","26068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451053","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-10","<p>The reporting, analysis and follow-up of occurrences in civil aviation is governed by Regulation (EU) No 376/2014 which was adopted on 3 April 2014 and became applicable on 15 November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The open reporting of safety occurrences is vital to help ensure that significant issues can be identified and addressed before they lead to an accident. To foster open reporting the Regulation aims to create a just culture in which occurrences can be reported without fear of any detriment. To support the just culture the Regulation requires that reports be given an appropriate level of confidentiality and that information derived from occurrence reports shall be used only for safety related purposes. However, the Regulation does permit information to be released on request to interested parties that have a genuine safety related need for the information.</p><p> </p><p>The Regulation also recognises the need to keep the public informed on aviation safety matters. It requires Member States to publish, at least annually, a safety review setting out the type of occurrences and safety-related information that has been reported, any trends that have been identified and any corrective action taken. In addition, the European Aviation Safety Agency is required to include information about the analysis of occurrence reports in its annual safety review.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-10T13:20:32.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451053/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451053/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-05","Aviation: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with his European counterparts about EU proposals to block public access to Mandatory Occurrence Reports; and what assessment he has made of the potential effect of those proposals on public confidence in aircraft safety.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","26102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451054","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-10","<p>The identified impact on the Regent’s Park hedgehog population is from the provision of replacement car parking for the Zoological Society of London rather than from lorries accessing the proposed lorry holding area. The measures being considered to mitigate this effect in the Regent’s Park area do not require an Additional Provision to the Bill. Any mitigation measures outside the limits of the Bill would be delivered with the cooperation of The Royal Parks.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-10T13:06:36.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451054/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451054/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-05","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24387, whether the proposed changes to mitigate the effect of lorry traffic on the hedgehog population in the area of Regent's Park will require an amendment to the High Speed Rail (London - West Midlands) Bill.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","26120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451055","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-15","<p>The scope for Midland Main Line electrification includes making appropriate adjustment to the Fast Line Overhead Line Equipment between London St Pancras and Bedford South Junction.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-15T11:03:30.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451055/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451055/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-05","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what works will be required south of Bedford to enable Midland Mainline electrification north of Bedford.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","26028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451056","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-10","<p>The identified impact on the Regent’s Park hedgehog population is from the provision of replacement car parking for the Zoological Society of London rather than from lorries accessing the proposed lorry holding area. Therefore, no assessment has been made of changing the route used by HS2 construction vehicles in the Regent’s Park area for the purpose of mitigating the impact on hedgehogs. Such a change would require an Additional Provision to the Bill.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-10T13:14:07.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451056/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451056/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-05","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24387, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of changing the route used by lorries involved in the High Speed 2 construction away from the hedgehog population in the Regent's Park area as an alternative to establishing replacement habitats; and whether such a change would require an amendment to the High Speed Rail (London - West Midlands) Bill.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","26121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451057","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-10","<p>During the recent spending review, the Department made clear to the British Transport Police Authority that it considered that appropriate efficiencies should be identified and made. However, it also emphasised that any efficiencies identified should not materially impact on the operational policing capability of the British Transport Police, including in relation to counter-terrorist activity. The British Transport Police Authority identified savings of over 8% that can be made between 2016/17 and 2019/20 from the British Transport Police’s (BTP) core policing budgets, focussed on those areas where reductions would not have a material operational impact on the rail network. The Department has set out its expectation that these savings should be achieved during the course of the spending review period. Any efficiency savings could, however, potentially be reinvested into counter-terrorist activities, depending on the need.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-10T13:22:51.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451057/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451057/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-05","British Transport Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 25019, what efficiency savings he expects the British Transport Police to make in cash terms in each year up to 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","26116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451058","Women and Equalities","false","2016-02-10","<p>My answer of 1 February 2015 to Questions 24538 and 24539 detailed all meetings that the Secretary of State for Education and Minister for Women and Equalities and I have had with representatives of the FTSE 100 and other businesses. We have also spoken at a number of conferences and events, with representatives from across the FTSE 350 and other businesses in attendance. We always ensure that we use these opportunities to raise the issue of achieving a better gender balance on boards.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-02-10T16:09:57.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451058/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451058/answer",,,,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-02-05","Females: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2016 to Question 24539, whether the list provided in that answer includes all of the chief executives of FTSE 100 companies she has held meetings with to discuss the issue of increasing the number of women on company boards since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","26099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451059","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-10","<p>The current Universal Jobmatch service is delivered through a managed service by Monster Worldwide Ltd. Monster have built into the service some screening and monitoring tools which help to detect, deter and remedy inappropriate use of the site. Further to this, the Department carries out its own checks to ensure that Universal Jobmatch continues to deliver a safe and effective service for jobseekers and employers.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-10T13:12:32.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451059/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451059/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-05","Employment Schemes: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has contracted out the maintenance and screening arrangements for Universal Jobmatch.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","26097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451060","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-10","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the reply given on the 25 January 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-20/23428/" target="_blank">UIN 23428</a>.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-10T13:15:38.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451060/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451060/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-05","Employment and Support Allowance: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with Parkinson's disease have been placed in the (a) support group and (b) work-related activity group with a prognosis statement of (i) three months, (ii) six months, (iii) 12 months, (iv) 18 months, (v) two years and (vi) more than two years since the introduction of employment and support allowance in 2008.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","26075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451061","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-10","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave the Hon. Member for Dulwich and West Norwood on 3 February 2016 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-29/24910" target="_blank">24910</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-10T16:51:44.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451061/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451061/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-05","Supported Housing: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to exempt supported accommodation from plans to cap social rents at local housing allowance rates.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","26073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451062","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-11","<p>It is important that savers know what costs and charges they are paying. As a first step towards achieving this, most occupational pension schemes offering money purchase benefits are now required to report the charges levied on members and, as far as they are able, transaction costs, via an annual Chair’s Statement. The Chair’s Statement, which must be given to beneficiaries and recognised trade unions on request, must also report the trustees’ view on the extent to which these costs present value for members.</p><p> </p><p>Similarly, the Financial Conduct Authority have made rules requiring Independent Governance Committees to report annually on the value for money offered by workplace personal pension schemes, taking into account scheme charges and transaction costs.</p><p> </p><p>The government is committed to ensuring that members of pension schemes are also able to obtain information about all the costs and charges which they bear. Last year, the Government and the FCA jointly carried out a call for evidence on disclosure of transaction costs in pension schemes, and we are currently planning our next steps.</p><p> </p><p>Many pension schemes which invest in pooled funds do so via institutional versions of retail funds, for which costs other than the disclosed investment management fee will be similar. Retail funds will be covered by the Packaged Retail Investment and Insurance Products (PRIIPs) Regulation, which will apply from the end of 2016 and provides for enhanced minimum standards of disclosure.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-11T08:42:34.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451062/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451062/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-05","Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure cost transparency from pooled retail pension funds.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","26069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451063","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-10","<p>PIP is continuing to roll out in a safe and steady manner and as such there will be a variety of cases, and case volumes, within the system at any one time. Variation in Mandatory Reconsideration outcomes is to be expected in a live system of this scale as applications are decided on an individual basis.</p><p>There are no targets for Mandatory Reconsideration outcomes.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-10T11:54:45.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451063/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451063/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-05","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the decrease in the number of personal independence payment mandatory reconsideration new decisions in cases in which awards were changed between July 2014 and October 2015.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","26022"
